### Exploring the Data

#### High Level Data Analysis on Country Credit Ratings

**What you need to do:** First thing you should do once the data has been cleaned and enriched is to check things looks OK at the highest possible level: even before you delve into the sample dataset's numbers, you want to make sure that the existing categories and those you've derived works well separately and more importantly works together to provides (logically) the correct information to the investor that makes absolute sense.

**Why you need to do it:** From your experience with country credit ratings, you know that its purpose is to tell a potential investor how much 'trust' they can put into the country's financial institutions' ability to pay them back the money they've invested. In basic terms it's the likelihood of default on payment (be it loan-generated interest, bond coupons, share dividends or the actual loan amount) on a borrowing made by the country using financial instruments (e.g. a bond). However, from your background, you also know that countries with a weaker credit rating would normally give an incentive to the lender like better rates of return, which tends to attract investors with higher appetite for risk (think: higher risk usually means higher rewards).

**How you plan to analyse the country's credit rating:** First thing is to create a category to enable to countries to be split into known economic, geo-political, or geographical groups. As the dataset is a 'static' snapshot, you will also find it much easier to look at the data using grouping of countries. This will enable you to find the relevant patterns, trends, etc for a specific country group to then drill-down to find out through further analysis at a more granular (read as country-specific) level if needed. From your conversation with your fiend over coffee, you will decide the country groups you have chosen make the most sense, as well as including all the countries within your sample data.

**What information does this provide investors looking to buy the Global Index ETF:** At the highest level - this provides the investor with the amount of country risk so they are able to gauge how much they should invest (e.g. what percent of their investment should be allocated to that index ETF). Again, this depends on the type of investor, with risk-adverse investors opting for lower returns on prime or investment graded countries rather than higher earnings from non-investment or more speculative grade countries). The information you've gleaned from the dataset matches credit risk to other influencing factors like the countries' banking sector health, political risk and real estate index values so that you're able to expand on the data analysis for the investor to make their decisions.

From researching the internet, you then find out the relationship between each of the Categories and adopt the following to prove:

- **_Assumption#1 (A1): Country's Political Risk Score_ vs its _Banking Sector Health:_** _A higher political risk score means a safer banking environment, while a lower score means the banking sector is likely to struggle more due to political instability and related problems._
- **_Assumption#2 (A2): Country's Credit Rating (S&P) vs its Banking Sector Health:_** _A higher S&P credit rating for a country is linked to a healthier, more stable banking sector. A lower rating usually means the banking sector is more vulnerable due to economic and financial risks._
- **_Assumption#3 (A3): Country's Credit Rating (S&P) vs its Real Estate Index:_** _A higher S&P credit rating generally means a healthier real estate market, while a lower rating indicates more risk and instability in real estate values and investments. You may wish to use this as the 'control group' to make sure the above A2 assumption still stands._

#### A view into the Global Stock Markets

**What you need to do:** After you're done with analysing the country's credit ratings (and the results are expected and they all make sense), you are now ready to start looking into the underlying numbers. The best place to begin is to have a look at the numbers connected with the country's stock exchanges and commodity indexes.

**Why you need to do it:** First thing you need to do is find out what ETFs are and how they are linked with indexes - global or otherwise.

Your research into this shows that before ETFs were created, if an investor wanted to buy 1 share in all stocks listed on the Footsie 100 (or FTSE 100 or the 100 largest company by market capitalisation as listed on the London Stock Exchange) - they would have to purchase each share _separately_. You appreciate this took an enormous amount of time and effort to achieve to 'track' just one index.

What Exchange Traded Funds (ETFs) are essentially (for our intent and purpose) is a basket of stock (and/or other financial assets) for a given index, whereby someone else buys and keeps the 1 share of each of the 100 FTSE stock, then they issue a single ETF (based upon the underlying assets they hold on your behalf) that investors can by via an exchange (hence the exchange traded element). The benefit of an ETF lies in its risk-reduction through diversification (for example, not all 100 companies will all do well, nor will they all do badly at the same point in time giving the investor a way to mitigate their investment risk). Same goes for different types of financial assets, some may go up or down when influenced by different economic factors (e.g. rising inflation).

You find out how usage of and the variety of ETFs has expanded considerably (note: you can now get ETFs where the underlying assets are one or many types of crypto currencies) since its conception, to cover a diverse range indexes around the world, including global indexes (depending on the ETF in question covers a single country or multitude of countries in its basket on indexes) - enabling corporate investors (say Apple Computers) to be able to conveniently (through numerous electronic exchange) buy and sell stock indexed funds across the world. The composition of ETFs has also changed since its beginning, so instead of underlying shares, you can also get underlying bonds (i.e. government debt), or sometimes a mixture of both. For the sake of simplicity, and to limit the scope of your research\*, you will only look at ETFs backed by stock and/or bond assets for your friend.

_(\*note to yourself - the scope of your research should not be too extensive, as your main task is to analyse the data aspects, but then again, a good background in the subject matter will greatly help you choose what and how to visualize the dataset)_

**How you plan to analyse the global stock market health:**

Here, you may want to check the following:

- What's the usual amount of daily market movement (change) in general.
- Contrast that against the year-to-date currency change and see if there's a pattern/trend (i.e. can one predict the other).
- Find any abnormal market movement and/or changes in currency within the data provided and try to explain as to why before ruling out any outliers.

Like with the country credit ratings analysis, after carrying out the initial checks, it's best that you start from a country group level and drill-down deeper to find the root of what's happened. At the same time, you think that your friend's investors would also want to know the essential information needed to decide where to invest or avoid depending on their investment goals/strategy (e.g. some of your friend's potential investor clients may be interested in day trading so has an appetite for high market volatility wanting high returns within a single day whereas some others would want to keep their exposure to market risk at minimum levels).

**What information does this provide investors looking to buy the Global Index ETF:** Here stock market volatility is the key. You find out from your research that ETF pricing is highly sensitive to interest rate changes, country's local currency changes (against the US dollar). Other economic factors also play a big part, but you'll discuss those in a later. For now, you are just interested in looking at data related to the country's stock exchange before we move on.

#### Key Correlation Analysis & Economic Data Review

### **What you need to do:**

This is where you'll do most of your data analysis work: reviewing which economic factors are correlated with each other and finding both strongly positive and negative correlations. You will also look at some of the economic percentages ranges to see how well their data fits overall with your ideas about the regular and irregularity of movement distribution pattern (perception of normal vs irregular changes in the percentage values).

### **Why you need to do it:**

From your research into Global Index ETFs, you find out they are influenced by economic factors (like for example, the country's interest and inflation rates). ETFs pricing and value are also determined by two or more economic factors either moving the same way (positively correlated) or moving in opposite directions (negatively correlated). Here, you will only look at cases where factors are strongly correlated to find out if your data corresponds to what you find from your research into ETFs.

Your main goal here is to find a way to determine HOW the country group's Global ETFs may react when economic factors move towards or away from each other (for example if both inflation rate and interest rates rise, how should this impact the pricing of the Global Index ETF for say the BRIC collective of countries?).

Your secondary goal is the see the likeliness of the occurrence of high volatility (i.e. strong unexpected movements in value changes) for the key economic indicators, these movements may shift the Global ETFs prices up and down unexpectedly throughout the course of their exchange trading cycle.

_In essence, you're seeing if the data from your dataset follows to the rules prescribed by predetermined economic principles on ETFs._

**How you plan to review the key correlation analysis and economic percentages:**

To start with you should use just the percentage/ratio values within the dataset. From the whole dataset, you create a data frame pulling in just the feature/columns with percentage and the derived ratio values. You'd want to use the Pandas library to correlate these key features and see if there are any strong correlations (both positive and negative). Afterwards, if there's too much 'noise' in the correlation visuals, you may need to reduce the number of correlations by using code to create a subset data frame which select just strong correlations (say correlation of 90% and over)

You would then throw this new data frame into a few graphs and plots to visualize the correlation (sampling a few strongly positive and strongly negative) note the results and apply it to what you've researched to see if both your results and the underlying de-facto economic principles are well aligned

You will then use visualization, for each country group, the distribution of key economic factors, which will give your insight on how close (more likely to be volatile or prone to outliers) and dispersed (less likely to be volatile and less prone to outliers) the values are

At this point, you also think it would be helpful if the sample dataset your friend provided to you had a range of Global Index ETF prices as you could use it to feed some Machine Learning models, which will also help with this and other parts of your analysis, however she did say use this sample set to prove the value of data analysis and you can also persuade her to go down the ML path at some later point

### **Your Research Key Points Summary:**

- When interest and inflation rates rise - bond prices fall, so Global ETFs prices also fall
- Global Index ETF prices rise is linked to strong GDP growth, increase in foreign investments and healthy trade balances (i.e. export being bigger than your imports).
- The level of ETF price changes is also determined by what the ETF is created out of (e.g. bonds and stocks) as well as other considerations like geographic focus (e.g. country group that issued the bonds and/or stock) and sector exposure (e.g. stocks in technology or agricultural products).
- Strongly positive correlation tends to negatively impact the price of stock-based and bond-based Global Index ETFs but may positively impact commodity-based ETFs.
- Unlike you would anticipate, strongly negative correlation may not cancel each other out regarding how they impact Global Index ETF pricing but may increase the Global Index ETF pricing to other economic factors e.g. global market risk - so the investor should anticipate more price volatility (increase of price fluctuations) and asymmetry (i.e. less price distribution around the mean value but instead to either side of the graph)
